    <head>
        <title>Linear Relationships (8 of 8)</title>
        <objref idref="use_least_squares_regression"/>
    </head>
    <body>
       
        <p>Let's go back now to our motivating example, in which we wanted to predict the maximum
            distance at which a sign is legible for a
            60<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150021-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150021-0400" content=" "?>year<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150024-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150024-0400" content=" "?>old.
            Now that we have found the least squares
            <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150137-0400" comment="Suggest replacing graphic to clarify formula to &quot;Distance = 576 + (-3 * Age)&quot;"?>regression
            line<?oxy_comment_end?>, this prediction becomes quite easy: <image style="block"
                src="../webcontent/linear15.gif" alt="The scatterplot for Driver Age and Sign Legibility
Distance. Now that we have a regression line, finding out the maximum distance at which a sign is legible
for a 60-year-old person is easy. We simply check at what y coordinate does the regression line cross
a vertical line at x = 60. This happens to be at y = 396."/>
        </p>
        <p>Practically, what the figure tells us is that in order to find the predicted legibility
            distance for a
            60<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150358-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150358-0400" content=" "?>year<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150401-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150401-0400" content=" "?>old,
            we plug Age = 60 into
            <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150414-0400" content="the equation of "?>the
            regression line equation, to find that: <formula style="block">Predicted distance = 576
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150428-0400"?>+
                (<?oxy_insert_end?>- 3 *
                60<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150433-0400"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
                = 396</formula>
        </p>
        <p>396 feet is our best prediction for the maximum distance at which a sign is legible for a
            60<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150522-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150522-0400" content=" "?>year<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150524-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150524-0400" content=" "?>old.</p>
        <section purpose="didigetthis">
            <title>Did I Get This?</title>
            <body>
                <p><em>Background: </em>A statistics department is interested in tracking the
                    progress of its students from entry until graduation. As part of the study, the
