                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150545-0400"?>10<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150544-0400" content="ten"?>
                    students in an introductory course and in an
                    upper<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150553-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150553-0400" content=" "?>level
                    course required for graduation. The scatterplot below includes the least squares line<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150621-0400" content=","?>
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150622-0400"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>the
                    line that best explains the
                    upper<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150629-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150629-0400" content=" "?>level
                    course average based on the
                    lower<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150633-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150633-0400" content=" "?>level
                    course
                    average<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T150636-0400"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>,
                    and its equation: </p>
                <image src="../webcontent/linear21.gif" alt="The scatterplot for Introductory
Course Average vs. Upper Level Course Average. In addition to the data plotted on the scatterplot,
we have a least squares regression line. The line's equation is Y = -1.4 + X."/>
