        <section>
            <title>Comment About Predictions</title>
            <body>
                <p>Suppose a government agency wanted to design a sign appropriate for an even wider
                    range of drivers than were present in the original study.
                    <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190415-0400" content="Therefore, t"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190420-0400"?>T<?oxy_insert_end?>hey
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190423-0400"?>want<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190425-0400" content="sought"?>
                    to predict the maximum distance at which the sign
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190359-0400"?>would
                    be<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190403-0400" content="is"?>
                    legible for a
                    90<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190406-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190406-0400" content=" "?>year<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190409-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190409-0400" content=" "?>old.
                    Using the least squares regression line again as our summary of the linear
                    dependence of the distances upon the drivers' ages, the agency predicts that
                    90<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190504-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190504-0400" content=" "?>year<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190506-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190506-0400" content=" "?>old
                    drivers can see
                    th<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190512-0400"?>e<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190511-0400" content="at"?>
                    sign at no more than
                    576<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190530-0400"?> +<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190533-0400"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>- 3<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190543-0400"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>*
                    90<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190545-0400"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    = 306 feet: <image style="block" src="../webcontent/linear16.gif" alt="
The scatterplot for Driver Age vs. Sign Legibility Distance. The scales of both axes have been
enlarged so that the regression line has room on the right to be extended past where data exists.
The regression line is negative, so it grows from the upper left to the lower right of the plot.
Where the regression line is creating an estimate in between existing data, it is red. Beyond that,
where there are no data points, the line is green. This area is x&gt;82. The equation of the
regression line is Distance = 576 - 3 * Age"/>
                </p>
                <p>(The green segment of the line is the region of ages beyond 82, the age of the
                    oldest individual in the
                    study<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190557-0400"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?>)</p>
              
                <inquiry>
                    <question>Is our prediction for
                        90<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191603-0400"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191603-0400" content=" "?>year-old
                        drivers reliable?</question>
                    <answer>Our original age data ranged from 18 (youngest driver) to 82 (oldest
                        driver), and our regression line is therefore a summary of the linear
                        relationship
                            <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190711-0400" comment="use italics rather than bold for emphasis"?><em>in
                            that age range only<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190742-0400"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190741-0400" content="!"?>
                            <?oxy_comment_end?></em> When we plug the value 90 into the regression
                        line equation, we are assuming that the same linear relationship extends
                        beyond the range of our age data (18-82) into the green segment. <em>There
                            is no justification for such an
                            assumption<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190748-0400"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190748-0400" content="!"?></em>
                        It might be the case that the vision of drivers older than 82 falls off more
                        rapidly than it does for younger drivers. (i.e., the
                        slope<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190807-0400" content="s"?>
                        changes from -3 to something more negative). Our prediction for age =
                        90<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190830-0400" content=","?>
                        is therefore
                            <em><?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190919-0400" comment="use italics instead of bold for emphasis. Keep bold on above sentence (there is no justification ...) for added emphasis."?>not
                            reliable<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190835-0400"?>.<?oxy_comment_end?><?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190835-0400" content="!"?></em>
                    </answer>
                </inquiry>
                <!--
				<stats:question>Is our prediction for 90 year-old drivers reliable?</stats:question>
				<stats:answer>Our original age data ranged from 18 (youngest driver) to 82 (oldest driver), and our regression line is therefore a summary of the linear relationship <em>in that age range only! </em> When we plug the value 90 into the regression line equation, we are assuming that the same linear relationship extends beyond the range of our age data (18-82) into the green segment. <em>There is no justification for such an assumption!</em> It might be the case that the vision of drivers older than 82 falls off more rapidly than it does for younger drivers. (i.e., the slopes changes from -3 to something more negative). Our prediction for age = 90, is therefore <em>not reliable!</em></stats:answer>
-->
            </body>
        </section>
        <section>
            <title>In General</title>
            <body>
                <p>Prediction for ranges of the explanatory variable that are not in the data is
                    called <em>extrapolation</em>. Since there is no way of knowing whether a
                    relationship holds beyond the range of the explanatory variable in the data,
                    extrapolation is not
                    reliable<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T190953-0400"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    and should be avoided. In our
                    example<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191001-0400"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    like most others, extrapolation can lead to very poor or illogical predictions. </p>
                <activity idref="linear8lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>
            </body>
        </section>
        <section>
            <title>Let's Summarize</title>
            <body>
                <ul>
                    <li>A special case of the relationship between two quantitative variables is the
                            <em>linear </em>relationship. In this case, a straight line simply and
                        adequately summarizes the relationship.</li>
                    <li>When the scatterplot displays a linear
                        relati<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191044-0400" content="i"?>onship,
                        we supplement it
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191119-0400"?>with<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191118-0400" content="by"?>
                        the <em>correlation coefficient
                            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191126-0400"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>r<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191127-0400"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?></em>,
                        which measures the <em>strength</em> and
                        <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191151-0400" comment="make bold to indicate terminology"?>direction<?oxy_comment_end?>
                        of a linear relationship between two quantitative variables. The correlation
                        ranges between -1 and 1. Values near -1 indicate a strong negative linear
                        relationship, values near 0 indicate a weak linear relationship, and values
                        near 1 indicate a strong positive linear relationship.</li>
                    <li>The correlation is only an appropriate numerical measure for linear
                        relationships, and is sensitive to outliers. Therefore, the correlation
                        should only be used as a supplement to a scatterplot (after we look at the
                        data).</li>
                    <li>The most commonly used criterion for
                        fi<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191240-0400"?>nd<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191239-0400" content="tt"?>ing
                        a line that summarizes the pattern of a linear relationship is
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191255-0400"?>"<?oxy_insert_end?>least
                        squares.<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191259-0400"?>"<?oxy_insert_end?>
                        The <em>least squares regression line </em> has the smallest sum of squared
                        vertical deviations of the data points from the line.</li>
                    <li>The slope of the least squares regression line can be interpreted as the
                        average change in the response variable when the explanatory variable
                        increase<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191321-0400"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?>
                        by 1 unit.</li>
                    <li>The least
                        square<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191335-0400"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?>
                        regression line
                        predict<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191338-0400"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?>
                        the value of the response variable for a given value of the explanatory
                        variable. <em>Extrapolation</em> is prediction
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191354-0400"?>of<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191352-0400" content="for"?>
                        values of the explanatory variable that fall outside the range
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191404-0400"?>of<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T191402-0400" content="in"?>
                        the data. Since there is no way of knowing whether a relationship holds
                        beyond the range of the explanatory variable in the data, extrapolation is
                        not reliable, and should be avoided.</li>
                </ul>
            </body>
        </section>
